Date: Wed 22 Oct 2014
Source: The Telegraph [edited]
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11181135/French-winemakers-demand-action-on-incurable-grape-disease-devastating-vines.html


'Incurable' grape disease devastating vines
-------------------------------------------
French winemakers have demanded emergency funding to deal with an "incurable" grape disease, which they fear could become devastating and destroy the nation's vineyards.

The resurgence of the fungal disease esca was detected in mid-August [2014] on sauvignon vines in the Loire Valley. It has now spread elsewhere in France [and] infected 13 per cent of France's vines this year [2014], costing the industry more than Euro 1 billion [USD 1.27 billion].

Esca is transmitted by airborne spores and the only known treatment, sodium arsenite, is banned because it is carcinogenic. Once esca is detected, vines have to be ripped up and burned. Vineyard owners are facing catastrophic costs because their yields have fallen drastically and they have been forced to plant new vines.

French wine industry leaders are urging the European Union and national governments to declare esca an international emergency and provide funding to step up research to find a cure or a preventive treatment. Guy Vasseur, [France] Chambers of Agriculture, said more needed to be done. "We've got to work out how how to deal with this. It's potentially more serious than people seem to realise," he said.

Lifting the ban on sodium arsenite has been ruled out on health grounds. "The problem is that because sodium arsenite worked, there was no research for years on an alternative," Michel Badier, Loir-et-Cher chamber of agriculture, said.

[byline: David Chazan]

