communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Esca is a complex disease syndrome involving several fungal species. It is considered a series of pathological events starting in the nursery and finishing when the plant is mature. Esca is an important problem for grape production worldwide and historic evidence suggests that it may have been around since the start of viticulture. With climate warming and similar to other fungal diseases, it has extended its range in the last decades.

Esca presents 2 different types of symptoms: one characterised by leaf alterations, including interveinal yellowing and necrosis, and brown spots on fruit ("measles"), the other by wood degradation and sudden death of the plant. Species reported so far to be associated with the different symptoms in different areas, include _Phaeoacremonium chlamydosporum_, _P. aleophilum_, _Eutypa lata_, _Stereum hirsutum_, _Phellinus igniarius_, and _Sphaeropsis malorum_. It is suggested that the different pathogens play different roles in the process which starts with leaf discolourations and eventually leads to wood degradation.

Where chemical control with sodium arsenite is not permitted, eliminating infected plants and pruning affected plant parts have been suggested to control the disease. Removal of infected material from the vineyard is essential since masses of spores are produced by the fungi even at low temperatures. Spores can be airborne, but can also be spread with plant material, water, contaminated equipment and by mechanical means.

